  "prompt": "Why are there two capital letters in the surname McCall?",
  "response": "The surname \"McCall\" features a capital \"M\" followed by \"c,\" which is a common stylistic choice in certain Scottish and Irish surnames. \"Mc\" or \"Mac\" means \"son of\" in Gaelic, so the \"M\" is capitalized for clarity, indicating the start of the surname, while \"c\" remains lowercase. Therefore, \"McCall\" can be interpreted as meaning \"son of Call.\" This convention is typical in many Gaelic surnames, where the \"Mac\" or \"Mc\" prefix is used to denote lineage.",
